# Property Tax Rate in Leander TX (2025) — Plus Cedar Park Comparison

If you're buying a home — or already own one — in Leander or Cedar Park, Texas, property taxes are one of the biggest numbers you need to understand. Texas has no state income tax, but property taxes are among the highest in the country. Here's exactly what to expect.

---

## What Is the Property Tax Rate in Leander, TX?

Leander's **combined property tax rate is approximately 2.0%–2.3%** of your home's assessed value. That number isn't one single rate — it's made up of several taxing entities stacked together:

| Taxing Entity | Approximate Rate |
|---|---|
| Leander ISD | ~1.10% |
| City of Leander | ~0.45% |
| Williamson County | ~0.39% |
| EMS / Other Districts | ~0.05%–0.10% |
| **Total** | **~2.0%–2.3%** |

> **Real example:** On a $450,000 home in Leander, you could expect to pay roughly **$9,000–$10,350 per year** in property taxes — or about $750–$860/month added to your mortgage payment.

---

## What Is the Property Tax Rate in Cedar Park, TX?

Cedar Park falls in both Williamson County and Travis County depending on the area, but most of Cedar Park runs through Williamson County and also falls under **Leander ISD** — the same school district as Leander.

| Taxing Entity | Approximate Rate |
|---|---|
| Leander ISD | ~1.10% |
| City of Cedar Park | ~0.38% |
| Williamson County | ~0.39% |
| EMS / Other Districts | ~0.05% |
| **Total** | **~1.9%–2.0%** |

Cedar Park tends to run **slightly lower than Leander** primarily because of a lower city rate and fewer MUD (Municipal Utility District) overlays — but the difference is often just $500–$1,000/year on a typical home.

