## How Texas Property Taxes Are Calculated

Texas property taxes are based on your home's **appraised value** as determined by the county appraisal district (in this case, Williamson Central Appraisal District or WCAD).

The formula is simple:

**Appraised Value × Tax Rate = Annual Tax Bill**

But here's the catch: WCAD appraises homes every year, and values have been rising fast across the Austin metro. That means even if the tax *rate* stays the same, your bill can go up significantly year over year.

---

## How to Lower Your Property Tax Bill in Leander or Cedar Park

### 1. File a Homestead Exemption
If this is your primary residence, you qualify for a **homestead exemption** that reduces your appraised value by up to 20% for school taxes — and caps annual increases at 10%. This is the single biggest thing you can do. File at [wcad.org](https://www.wcad.org).

**Deadline: April 30th of the tax year.**

### 2. Protest Your Appraisal
Every homeowner has the right to protest their appraised value. Williamson County appraisals frequently come in higher than market value, and many homeowners successfully reduce their bill by $500–$2,000+ per year by protesting.

You can protest yourself online through WCAD or hire a property tax protest company (most work on contingency — they only get paid if you save money).

**Protest deadline: May 15th or 30 days after your notice is mailed.**

### 3. Check for Additional Exemptions
You may qualify for extra exemptions if you are:
- **65 or older** — school taxes are frozen
- **A disabled veteran** — significant exemptions based on disability rating
- **100% disabled** — full property tax exemption

